Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| API Found | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Remove — not needed with cooperative model |

## Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime cannot forcibly terminate a thread. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation** where the work voluntarily checks a `CancellationToken`.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable — always wrap in using
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run schedules work on the thread pool (no manual Thread needed)
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the token fires
            return Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token)
                       .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                       .GetAwaiter()
                       .GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

1. **`CancellationTokenSource(timeout)`** — auto-cancels after the deadline, replacing the `Join` + `Abort` pattern.
2. **`Task.WaitAsync(token)`** (.NET 6+) — waits for the task with a cancellation check, so the *caller* unblocks promptly at timeout.
3. **`catch (OperationCanceledException)`** — replaces `catch (ThreadAbortException)`. The `when` guard ensures we only catch our own timeout, not an unrelated cancellation.
4. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` removed** — no equivalent needed; cooperative cancellation doesn't inject exceptions.

## Critical Pitfall: The Work Delegate

> **`Task.WaitAsync` unblocks the caller, but the delegate may keep running.**

Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation can't force-stop `work()` if it doesn't cooperate. For full cancellation, refactor the delegate to accept a token:

```csharp
// Better: pass token through so work can cooperate
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(token), token)
                   .WaitAsync(token)
                   .GetAwaiter()
                   .GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Callers check the token at regular checkpoints:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

## Other Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers. Always `using`. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch at the top-level orchestration point (as shown). Let it propagate elsewhere. |
| **Blocking sync I/O inside the delegate** | `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Receive`, etc. won't respond to the token. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O. |
| **Fire-and-forget background work** | The orphaned task still holds references. Track it or log its completion to avoid silent failures. |
